# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-harding-loring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:charles-harding-loring/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:charles-harding-loring/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The **Allegheny Mountain Range** (/ˌælɪˈɡeɪni/ *AL-ih-GAY-nee*)—also spelled **Alleghany** or **Allegany**, less formally the **Alleghenies**—is part of the vast Appalachian Mountain Range of the Eastern United States and Canada.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Historically, it represented a significant barrier to westward land travel and development.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies have a northeast–southwest orientation, running for about 300 miles (480 km) from north-central Pennsylvania southward, through western Maryland and eastern West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies comprise the rugged western-central portion of the Appalachians.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] They rise to 4,862 feet (1,482 m) in northeastern West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the east, they are dominated by a high, steep escarpment known as the Allegheny Front.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the west, they slope down into the closely associated Allegheny Plateau, which extends into Ohio and Kentucky.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The principal settlements of the Alleghenies are Altoona, State College, and Johnstown, Pennsylvania; and Cumberland, Maryland.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Using the United States Geological Survey (USGS) classification of physical geography (physiography), the Allegheny Mountain range is part of the Appalachian Plateau province of the Appalachian Highlands physiographic division.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The name is derived from the Allegheny River, which drains only a small portion of the Alleghenies in west-central Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The meaning of the word, which comes from the Lenape (Delaware) Native Americans, is not definitively known but is usually translated as "fine river".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The suffix -ni means "of the", in Lenape, despite that geh is also Iroquoian for "of the".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] So, most likely, Alligehni or Oligini would be the Lenape name for the original homeland of the Erie people.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The word "Allegheny" was once commonly used to refer to the whole of what are now called the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] John Norton used it (spelled variously) around 1810 to refer to the mountains in Tennessee and Georgia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Around the same time, Washington Irving proposed renaming the United States either "Appalachia" or "Alleghania".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In 1861, Arnold Henry Guyot published the first systematic geologic study of the whole mountain range.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] His map labeled the range as the "Alleghanies", but his book was titled *On the Appalachian Mountain System*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] As late as 1867, John Muir—in his book *A Thousand Mile Walk to the Gulf*—used the word "Alleghanies" in referring to the *southern* Appalachians.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] There was no general agreement about the "Appalachians" versus the "Alleghanies" until the late 19th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] From northeast to southwest, the Allegheny Mountains run about 300 miles (480 km).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] From west to east, at their widest, they are about 100 miles (160 km).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] When combining the Allegheny Province with the Kanawa Province, they run 400 miles (640 km).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The USGS physiographic classification of all land in the United States lists the Allegheny Mountains as a section within the larger Appalachian Plateau province.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It may be generally defined to the south by the Allegheny Front, and to the east by the Susquehanna River valley.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] To the west, the Alleghenies grade down into the dissected Allegheny Plateau.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The westernmost ridges are considered to be the Laurel Highlands and Chestnut Ridge in Pennsylvania, and Laurel Mountain and Rich Mountain in West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Big Stone Ridge marks the southern extent of the Alleghenies and is an outlier of Flat Top Mountain, with the Tug Fork river running along its western flank.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The land to the south and to the west of the Alleghenies is the Valley and Ridge physiographic province.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The eastern edge of the Alleghenies is marked by the Allegheny Front, which is also sometimes considered the eastern terminus of the Allegheny Plateau.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] This great escarpment roughly follows a portion of the Eastern Continental Divide in this area.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Several gorges and valleys drain the Alleghenies: to the east, Smoke Hole Canyon (South Branch Potomac River), and to the west the New River Gorge and the Blackwater and Cheat Canyons.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Thus, about half the precipitation falling on the Alleghenies makes its way west to the Mississippi and half goes east to Chesapeake Bay and the Atlantic seaboard.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The highest ridges of the Alleghenies are just west of the Front, with an east/west elevational change of up to 3,000 feet (910 m).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Absolute elevations of the Allegheny Highlands reach nearly 5,000 feet (1,500 m), with the highest elevations in the southern part of the range.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The highest point in the Allegheny Mountains is Spruce Knob (4,863 ft; 1,482 m), on Spruce Mountain in West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies contain relatively few large urban centers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The four most populous cities in the region are, in descending order, Altoona, State College, and Johnstown in Pennsylvania, and Cumberland in Maryland.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the 1970s and 1980s, the Interstate Highway System was extended into the northern portion of the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The region is now served by a network of federal expressways—Interstates 80, 70/76 and 68.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Interstate 64 traverses the southern extremity of the range, but the Central Alleghenies (the "High Alleghenies" of eastern West Virginia) have posed challenges for highway planners owing to the region's rugged terrain and environmental sensitivities (see Corridor H).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The central Alleghenies continue to rely on a limited network of secondary highways, and the region maintains a lower population density compared to adjacent areas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the telecommunications field, a unique impediment to development in the central Allegheny region is the United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), a large rectangle of land—about 13,000 square miles (34,000 km2)—that straddles the border area of Virginia and West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Created in 1958 by the Federal Communications Commission, the NRQZ restricts all omnidirectional and high-power radio transmissions, although cell phone service is allowed throughout much of the area.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Much of the Monongahela (West Virginia), George Washington (West Virginia, Virginia) and Jefferson (Virginia) National Forests lie within the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies also include a number of federally designated wilderness areas, such as the Dolly Sods Wilderness, Laurel Fork Wilderness, and Cranberry Wilderness in West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The mostly completed Allegheny Trail, a project of the West Virginia Scenic Trails Association since 1975, runs the length of the range within West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The northern terminus is at the Mason–Dixon line and the southern is at the West Virginia-Virginia border on Peters Mountain.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The bedrock of the Alleghenies is mostly sandstone and metamorphosed sandstone, quartzite, which is extremely resistant to weathering.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Prominent beds of resistant conglomerate can be found in some areas, such as the Dolly Sods.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] When it weathers, it leaves behind a pure white quartzite gravel.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The rock layers of the Alleghenies were formed during the Appalachian orogeny.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Because of intense freeze-thaw cycles in the higher Alleghenies, there is little native bedrock exposed in most areas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The ground surface usually rests on a massive jumble of sandstone rocks, with air space between them, that are gradually moving down-slope.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The crest of the Allegheny Front is an exception, where high bluffs are often exposed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Mineral springs in the High Alleghenies attracted Native Americans and 18th century white settlers and provided a modest incentive to the local economy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The spas developing around these geological features include celebrated resorts that continue to cater to an exclusive clientele, such as The Greenbrier (White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia; hotel built 1858) and The Homestead (Hot Springs, Virginia; original lodge built 1766).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The High Alleghenies are noted for their forests of red spruce, balsam fir, and mountain ash, trees typically found much farther north.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Hardwood forests also include yellow birch (whose specific name *Betula alleghaniensis* refer to the mountain range), sugar and red maple, eastern hemlock, and black cherry.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] American beech, pine, oak, and hickory can also be found.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Chestnut trees used to be dominant throughout the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In some areas, it made up as much as 25 to 50 percent of the canopy, now they are found as stump sprouts as a result of blight.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The forests of the entire region are now almost all second- or third-growth forests, the original trees having been removed in the late 19th and (in West Virginia) early 20th centuries.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The wild onion known as the ramp (*Allium tricoccum*) is also present in the deeper forests.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Certain isolated areas in the High Alleghenies are well known for their open expanses of sphagnum bogs and heath shrubs (e.g., Dolly Sods, Cranberry Glades).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Many plant communities are indeed similar to those of sea-level eastern Canada.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] But the ecosystems within the Alleghenies are remarkably varied.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In recent decades, the many stages of ecologic succession throughout the area have made the region one of enduring interest to botanists.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The larger megafauna which once inhabited the High Alleghenies—elk, bison, mountain lion—were all exterminated during the 19th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] They survived longer in this area, however, than in other parts of the eastern United States.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Naturalist John James Audubon reported that by 1851 a few eastern elk (*Cervus canadensis canadiensis*) could still be found in the Alleghany Mountains but that by then they were virtually gone from the remainder of their range.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Mammals in the Allegheny region today include whitetail deer, chipmunk, raccoon, skunk, groundhog, opossum, weasel, field mouse, flying squirrel, cottontail rabbit, gray foxes, red foxes, gray squirrels, red squirrels and a cave bat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Bobcat, snowshoe hare, wild boar and black bear and coyote are also found in the forests and parks of the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Mink and beaver are much less often seen.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These mountains and plateau have over 20 species of reptiles represented as lizard, skink, turtle and snake.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Some of the icterid birds visit the mountains as well as the hermit thrush and wood thrush.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] North American migrant birds live throughout the mountains during the warmer seasons.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Occasionally, osprey and eagles can be found nesting along the streams.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The hawks and owls are the most common birds of prey.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The water habitats of the Alleghenies hold 24 families of fish.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Amphibian species number about 21, among them hellbenders, lungless salamanders, and various toads and frogs.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Alleghenies provide habitat for about 54 species of common invertebrate.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These include Gastropoda, slugs, leech, earthworms and grub worm.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Cave crayfish (*Cambarus nerterius*) live alongside a little over seven dozen cave invertebrates.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The indigenous people inhabiting the Allegheny Mountains emerged from the greater region's archaic and mound building cultures, particularly the Adena and Eastern Woodland peoples with a later Hopewellian influence.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These Late Middle Woodland culture people have been called the Montaine (c.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Their neighbors, the woodland Buck Garden culture, lived in the western valleys of the central Allegheny range.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Montaine sites extend from the tributaries of the upper Potomac River region south to the New River tributaries.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These also were influenced by the earlier Armstrong culture of the more southwestern portions northern sub-range of the Ouasioto (Cumberland) Mountains and by the more easterly Virginia Woodland people.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Late Woodland Montaine were less influenced by Hopewellian trade from Ohio, although similarly polished stone tools have been found among the Montaine sites in the Tygart Valley.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Small groups of Montaine people appear to have lingered much beyond their classically defined period in parts of the most mountainous valleys.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The watershed of the Monongahela River is within the northwestern Alleghenies, and it is from it that the Monongahela culture takes its name.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Godwin-Portman site (36AL39) located in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, had a possible Fort Ancient (c.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] AD 850 to 1680) presence during the 15th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Washington Boro ceramics have been found on the Barton (18AG3) and Llewellyn (18AG26) sites in Maryland on the northeastern slopes of the late Susquehannock sequence.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] AD 900 to 1630) are called the Drew Tradition in Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] George: "I believe that some of the Monongahela were of Algonquin origin....
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Other scholars have suggested that Iroquoian speakers were interacting with Late Monongahela people, and additional evidence is presented to confirm this.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It is thought that these ancient Alleghenians were pushed from the classic Huffman Phase of the eastern slopes of the Alleghenies to the Blue Ridge Mountains in western Virginia, which was eastern Siouan territory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In 1669, John Lederer and members of his party became the first Europeans to crest the Blue Ridge Mountains and the first to see the Shenandoah Valley and the Allegheny Mountains beyond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The proto-historic Alleghenies can be exampled by the earliest journals of the colonists.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] According to Batts and Fallows' September, 1671 Expedition, they found Mehetan Indians of Mountain "Cherokee-Iroquois" mix on the New River tributaries.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] This journal does not identify the "Salt Village", but, that the "Mehetan" were associated with these and today thought to be "Monetons", Siouans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] However, this journal does not identify the "Salt Village" below the Kanawha Falls, but, that simply the "Mehetan" were associated with these.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] He explained, below the "Salt Villages", a mass of hostile Indians had, implied, arrived and some believe these to be "Shanwans" of Vielles Expedition of 1692~94, ancient Shawnee.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In 1669, John Lederer of Maryland for the Virginia Colony and the Tennessee Cherokee had visited the mouth of the Kanawha and reported no hostilities on the lower streams of the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Mohetan representative through a Siouan translator explained to Mr Batts and Mr Fallon, Colonel Abraham Woods explorers 1671–72, that he (Moheton Native American) could not say much about the people below the "Salt Village" because they (Mountain Cherokee) were not associated with them.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Mohetan was armed by this time of 1671 for the Mohetan Representative was given several pouches of ammunition for his and the other's weapons as a token of friendship.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Somebody had already been trading within the central Alleghenies before the Virginians' historical record begins in the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Some earlier scholars found evidence these Proto-historics were either Cistercians of Spanish Ajacan Occuquan outpost on the Potomac River or Jesuits and their Kahnawake Praying Indians (Mohawk) on the Riviere de la Ronceverte.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The "Kanawha Madonna" may date from this period or earlier.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Where the New River breaks through Peters' Mountain—near Pearisburg, Virginia—the 1671 journal mentions the "Moketans had formerly lived".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] According to a number of early 17th century maps, the Messawomeake or "Mincquas" (Dutch) occupied the northern Allegheny Mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The "Shatteras" (an ancient Tutelo) occupied the Ouasioto Mountains and the earliest term Canaraguy (Kanawhans otherwise Canawest) on the 1671 French map occupied the southerly Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] They were associated with the Allegheny "Cherokee" and Eastern Siouan as trade-movers and canoe transporters.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Calicuas, an ancient most northern Cherokee, migrated or was pushed from the Central Ohio Valley onto the north eastern slopes of the Alleghenies of the ancient Messawomeake, Iroquois tradesmen to 1630s Kent Island, by 1710 maps.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Sometime before 1712, the Canawest ("Kanawhans"-"Canallaway"-"Canaragay") had moved to the upper Potomac and made a Treaty with the newly established trading post of Fort Conolloway which would become a part of western Maryland during the 1740s.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Prior to European exploration and settlement, trails through the Alleghenies had been transited for many generations by American Indian tribes such as the Iroquois, Shawnee, Delaware, Catawba and others, for purposes of trade, hunting and, especially, warfare.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Western Virginia "Cherokee" were reported at Cherokee Falls, today's Valley Falls of the Tygart Valley.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Indian trader Charles Poke's trading post dates from 1731 with the Calicuas of Cherokee Falls still in the region from the previous century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The "London Scribes" (The Crown's taxation records) vaguely mentions the colonial Alleghenian location of only a few other early colonial trading locations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] A general knowledge of these few outposts are more of traditional telling of some local people.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] However, an example is the "Van Metre" trading house mentioned in an earlier edition of the "Wonderful West Virginia Magazine" being on the South Branches of the upper reaches of the Potomac.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Another very early trading house appears on a lower Greenbrier Valley map during the earlier decades of the 18th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] As early as 1719, new arrivals from Europe began to cross the lower Susquehanna River and settle illegally in defiance of the Board of Property in Pennsylvania, on un-warranted land of the northeastern drainage rivers of the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Several Indian Nations requested the removal of "Maryland Intruders".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Some of these moved onward as territory opened up beyond the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The first permanent European settlers *west* of the Alleghenies have traditionally been considered to have been two New Englanders: Jacob Marlin and Stephen Sewell, who arrived in the Greenbrier Valley in 1749.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] They built a cabin together at what would become Marlinton, West Virginia, but after disputing over religion, Sewell moved into a nearby hollowed-out sycamore tree.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In 1751, surveyor John Lewis (father of Andrew Lewis) discovered the pair.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Sewell eventually settled on the eastern side of Sewell Mountain, near present-day Rainelle, West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] They may well have been the first to settle what was then called the "western waters"—*i.e.*, in the regions where streams flowed westward to the Gulf of Mexico rather than eastward to the Atlantic.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Among the first whites to penetrate into the Allegheny Mountains were surveyors attempting to settle a dispute over the extent of lands belonging to either Thomas Fairfax, 6th Lord Fairfax of Cameron or to the English Privy Council.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] An expedition of 1736 by John Savage established the location of the source of the North Branch Potomac River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In March 1742, a frontiersman named John Howard—along with his son and others—had been commissioned by Governor Gooch to explore the southwest of Virginia as far as the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Following Cedar Creek through the Natural Bridge, they floated in buffalo-skin boats down the New, Coal, Kanawha, and Ohio Rivers to the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Although captured by the French before he reached Natchez, Howard was eventually released and (in 1745) was interviewed by Fairfax.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Howard's description of the South Branch Potomac River resulted in the definite decision by Fairfax to secure his lands in the region.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] An expedition under Peter Jefferson and Thomas Lewis in the following year emplaced the "Fairfax Stone" at the source of the North Branch and established a line of demarcation (the "Fairfax Line") extending from the stone south-east to the headwaters of the Rappahannock River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Lewis' journal of that expedition provides a valuable view of the Allegheny country before its settlement.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Jefferson and Joshua Fry's "Fry-Jefferson Map" of 1751 accurately depicted the Alleghenies for the first time.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the following decades, pioneer settlers arrived in the Alleghenies, especially during Colonial Virginia's Robert Dinwiddie era (1751–1758).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These included squatters by the Quit-rent Law.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Some had preceded the official surveyors using a "hack on the tree and field of corn" marking land ownership approved by the Virginia Colonial Governor who had to be replaced with Governor John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Royal Proclamation of 1763, issued by King George III of Great Britain, followed a few months after the Treaty of Paris (1763), which formally ended the Seven Years' War and transferred French territory in North America to Great Britain.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation set a geographical limit that (at least temporarily) forbade all new settlements west of a line drawn along the crest of the Appalachian Mountains, which was delineated as an Indian Reserve.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Extending from New England in the north to Georgia in the south, the Proclamation Line effectively bisected the Alleghenies by more or less following the Eastern Continental Divide through the region.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation Line was not intended to be a permanent boundary between the colonists and Native American lands but rather a temporary boundary that could be extended further west in an orderly, lawful manner.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It was also not designed as an uncrossable boundary; people could cross the line, but not settle past it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Its contour was defined by the headwaters that formed the watershed along the crest of the mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] All land with rivers that flowed into the Atlantic was designated for the colonial entities.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In contrast, all the land with rivers that flowed into the Mississippi was reserved for the Native American populations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation outlawed the private purchase of Native American land, which had often created problems.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Instead, all future land purchases were to be made by Crown officials "at some public Meeting or Assembly of the said Indians".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] British colonials were forbidden to settle on native lands, and colonial officials were forbidden to grant ground or lands without royal approval.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Organized land companies asked for land grants, but this was denied by King George III.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] British colonists and land speculators objected to the proclamation boundary since the British government had already assigned land grants to them.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Including the wealthy owners of the Ohio company, who protested the line to the governor of Virginia, as they had plans to settle the land to grow the business.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Indeed, many settlements already existed beyond the Proclamation Line, some of which were temporarily evacuated during Pontiac's War (1763-1766) and there were many already granted land claims yet to be settled.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] For example, George Washington and his Virginia soldiers had been granted lands past the boundary.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Prominent American colonials joined with the land speculators in Britain to lobby the government to move the line further west.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The colonists' demands were met and the boundary line was adjusted in a series of treaties with the Native Americans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Even the temporary exclusion of settlers from this vast region created significant discontent between Britain and colonial land speculators and potential settlers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Many colonists disregarded the Proclamation Line and its successors and settled in the west, creating more tension between them and the Native Americans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Proclamation and access to western lands was one of the first major areas of dispute between Britain and the Thirteen Colonies and became a contributing factor leading to the American Revolution.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Trans-Allegheny travel had been facilitated when a military trail—Braddock Road—was blazed and opened by the Ohio Company in 1751.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] (It followed an earlier Indian and pioneer trail known as Nemacolin's Path.) Braddock Road connected Cumberland, Maryland (the upper limit of navigation on the Potomac River) and the forks of the Ohio River (the future Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It received its name from General Edward Braddock, the British commander of the North American phase of the Seven Years' War — known locally as the French and Indian War (1754–1763) — who led the ill-fated Braddock expedition four years later.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In addition to the war, hunting and trading with Indians were primary motivations for white movement across the mountains.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Permanent white settlement of the northern Alleghenies was facilitated by the explorations and stories of such noted Marylanders as the Indian fighter and trader Thomas Cresap (1702–1790) and the backwoodsman and hunter Meshach Browning (1781–1859).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] These immigrants were predominantly Scotch-Irish, German, and, to a lesser extent, British stock.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Braddock Road was superseded by the Cumberland Road—also called the National Road—one of the first major improved highways in the United States to be built by the federal government.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Construction began in 1811 at Cumberland and the road reached Wheeling, Virginia (now West Virginia) on the Ohio River in 1818.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Just to the south, the state-funded Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike was constructed to provide a direct route for the settlements of the Shenandoah Valley to the Ohio River by way of the Tygart Valley and Little Kanawha Rivers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Planned and approved in 1826 and completed in 1848, the Staunton and Parkersburg was maintained by fees (tolls) collected at toll houses placed at regular intervals.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Construction on the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad began at Baltimore in 1828; the B&O traversed the Alleghenies, changing the economy and society of the Mountains forever.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The B&O had reached Martinsburg, (West) Virginia, by May 1842, Hancock, (West) Virginia, by June, Cumberland, Maryland, on November 5, 1842, Piedmont, (West) Virginia, on July 21, 1851, and Fairmont, (West) Virginia, on June 22, 1852.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Chesapeake and Ohio Canal—also begun in 1828, but at Georgetown—was also a public work of enormous economic and social significance for the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It approached Hancock, Maryland, by 1839.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] From the beginning, the B&O Railroad and the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal operated in bitter legal and commercial competition with one another as they vied for rights to the narrow strips of land along the Potomac.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] When the Canal finally reached Cumberland in 1850, the Railroad had already arrived eight years before.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Debt-ridden, the Canal company dropped its plan to continue construction of the next 180 miles (290 km) of the Canal into the Ohio Valley.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The company had long realized—especially with the difficult experience of digging the Paw Paw Tunnel—that the original plan of construction over the mountains and all the way down the Youghiogheny River to Pittsburgh was "wildly unrealistic".
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Public works financed at the state level were not lacking during this period.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Main Line of Public Works was a transportation network project built between 1826 and 1834 by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] It created a railroad and canal system across southern Pennsylvania between Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, intended to transport freight (notably including anthracite coal) and people with greater reliability, speed and capacity.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Main Line of Public Works included the Philadelphia and Columbia Railroad, the Allegheny Portage Railroad and the Pennsylvania Canal system.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Lying astride the border separating the Union and Confederacy, the Alleghenies were among the areas most directly affected by the American Civil War (1861–1865).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] One of the earliest campaigns of the War was fought for control of the Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike and for the access it provided to the B&O Railroad.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Battle of Rich Mountain (July 11, 1861) gave the Federals control of the turnpike, of Tygart's Valley, and of all of the territory of western Virginia to the north and west, including the railroad.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] (Union General George McClellan's victory in this theater would ultimately bring him promotion to commander the Army of the Potomac.) The Federals fortified at Cheat Summit, and the Confederates established strongholds at Camp Bartow and Camp Allegheny.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Here they faced each other warily through the fall of 1861 and the following winter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Lee's attempt to attack Cheat Summit Fort (September 12–15, 1861) and Federal attempts to attack Bartow and Allegheny, all failed to change the strategic stalemate.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Finally, the harsh, high elevation winter achieved what the troops had failed to accomplish, and in the spring of 1862 both armies moved on down the pike to the Battle of McDowell (May 8, 1862), and then on to fight what became General Stonewall Jackson's Shenandoah Valley Campaign (spring 1862).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Two years later, much of this contested area (along with much else) became part of the new state of West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The very rugged terrain of the Alleghenies was not at all amenable to a large-scale maneuver war and so the actions that the area witnessed for the remainder of the conflict were generally guerrilla in nature.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] With the further spread of the railroad networks in the 1890s and early 1900s, many new towns developed and thrived in the Alleghenies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The lumbering and coal industries that boomed in the wake of the railroads brought a measure of prosperity to the region, but most of the revenues flowed out of the mountains to the cities of the eastern seaboard where the captains of industry were headquartered.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] This inequity created a bitter legacy that would last for generations and form the foundation of the mountaineers' poverty and the area's immense environmental degradation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The dam broke after several days of extremely heavy rainfall, unleashing 20 million tons of water (18 million cubic meters) from the reservoir known as Lake Conemaugh.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] (This body of water had been built as part of the Main Line of Public Works, then abandoned.) With a flow rate that temporarily equalled that of the Mississippi River, the flood killed 2,209 people and caused US$17 million of damage (about $425 million in 2012 dollars).
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The American Red Cross, led by Clara Barton and with 50 volunteers, undertook a major disaster relief effort.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Support for victims came from all over the United States and 18 foreign countries.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] After the flood, survivors suffered a series of legal defeats in their attempts to recover damages from the dam's owners.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Public indignation at that failure prompted the development in American law changing a fault-based regime to strict liability.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In the 1920s and '30s, Allegheny highways were extensively paved to provide access for automobiles.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The suffering occasioned by the Great Depression led to a major social experiment in 1933 aimed at providing opportunities for unemployed local miners and farmers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] Construction of the settlement of Arthurdale, West Virginia was undertaken by the short-lived Subsistence Homesteads Division and with the personal involvement of First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt, who used her influence to win government approval for the scheme.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The aim was to encourage self-sufficiency and reduce dependence on both market forces and welfare provision.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The experiment failed through a clash of ideologies, between a strong emphasis on accommodating those most in need yet also having qualifications to ensure that the community would be self-governed in a professional manner.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The entrepreneurial community spirit never took hold, and the project is generally remembered as a classic failure, though some of its original residents continued to defend its principles.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] From the 1950s to 1992, the United States government maintained a top secret continuity program known as Project Greek Island at The Greenbrier hotel in the Alleghenies of southern West Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] In August 1963, at the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Dr.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The Flight 93 National Memorial is located at the site of the crash of United Airlines Flight 93—which was hijacked in the September 11 attacks—in Stonycreek Township, Pennsylvania, about 2 miles (3.2 km) north of Shanksville.
[src:charles-harding-loring/allegheny-mountains] The memorial honors the passengers and crew of Flight 93, who stopped Al-Qaeda terrorists from reaching their intended target.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:charles-harding-loring/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:charles-harding-loring/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Loring was born on December 26, 1828, and is descended from two Pilgrim forefathers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] His father was William Price Loring, who was born in Boston in 1795, and who was in early life a silversmith, and afterwards served as an officer of the customs.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was also an early California pioneer, where he remained until within a few years of his death, which occurred in Boston in 1878.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] His mother, whose maiden name was Eliza Harding, was born in Haverhill, Massachusetts, in 1800 and bore her husband four daughters and two sons.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] As his educational period was before the day of technical schools, he followed the usual course of preparation for mechanical engineering and served a regular apprenticeship in the machine shop with Jabez Coney.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] At its close, in 1851, he entered the United States Navy as a third assistant engineer, attaining, by competitive examination, the highest place in a class of 14.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] His entrance was just too late to give him an opportunity for participation in the Mexican–American War, and by the time the American Civil War broke out he had passed through all the junior grades and had become a chief engineer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] While engaged in this duty he made a test of the first injector which came to this country.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] During the Civil War he was in active service the whole time, and during the first 18 months was fleet engineer of the North Atlantic Squadron, being attached to the steamer USS *Minnesota*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was on board this ship during the attacks of the CSS *Virginia* on the Northern fleet in the battle of Hampton Roads on March 8–9, 1862, when USS *Cumberland* was sunk and USS *Congress* burned, and when the *Minnesota* also was attacked.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] A little later he was detached from sea duty and sent to Cincinnati, Ohio, to supervise the construction of three river and harbor monitors and also of some light-draught sea monitors building there.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Subsequently, he was made general inspector of all the iron-clad steamers building west of the Allegheny Mountains, having in charge at one time 11 monitors building at Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, and St.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] It was about this time that the compound engine was coming into general use, and the same board was directed to make a study of the compound engine with a view to its introduction in naval vessels.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Of this board, Loring was senior member, and associated with him was Chief Engineer Charles Hinckley Baker.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] After a very exhaustive study of the subject, they recommended the introduction of compound engines and the abandonment of the simple form, and the conversion of a number of the engines which were on hand into compound engines.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Four sets of these simple engines were so converted and were fitted to the USS *Vandalia*, USS *Marion*, USS *Quinnebaug*, and USS *Swatara*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] The tests of these engines were very satisfactory and showed a coal economy for short runs of not much over two pounds of coal per horsepower hour.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] This study of the compound engine made it natural that Loring should be selected as the representative of the Navy Department when, in 1874, he and Charles E.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] These tests were the first of the kind conducted under circumstances of entire reliability, with the result that the report of the trials was republished all over the world and is still quoted in all the text books on steam engineering.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Loring's next tour of sea duty was as a fleet engineer of the Asiatic Squadron on the USS *Tennessee*, where he had as his chief assistant, George W.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Melville, who later became his successor as Chief of the Bureau of Steam Engineering.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] There was nothing especially eventful in this cruise, and at its end, in 1880, he was assigned as the head of the steam engineering department of the New York Navy Yard.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] This was the period of greatest inactivity in the history of the Navy, and there was little to do, even for a very active man, except routine work.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Loring was senior member of a board that made a test of the machinery of the *Anthracite*, a little yacht with a triple-expansion engine working with 600 pounds pressure.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] The experiments were valuable as showing that, with the form of apparatus on board the *Anthracite*, there was no such gain in economy as to warrant the tremendous pressure carried, while it involved numerous practical difficulties.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] In 1881, he was a member of what is known as the First Naval Advisory Board, appointed by Secretary William H.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Hunt to formulate a shipbuilding program for the Navy which he might submit to Congress.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] The personnel of this advisory board was distinguished in all its branches, and the work they did made possible our splendid fleet of today, as they definitely decided to abandon wooden hulls for those of iron and steel, and for general progress in every respect.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] In 1882, he was a member of another important board known as the Navy Yard Board, of which Admiral Stephen Luce was senior member.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] The duty of this board was to visit all the navy yards of the country for the purpose of determining which of them might with advantage and economy be closed.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] It was a delicate task, but the report, when finally approved, gave general satisfaction, and its recommendations were carried out.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] On the retirement of the engineer-in-chief, William H.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Shock, only two successors were thought of, one of whom was Loring, and his merit and thorough qualification for the position were so well recognized that the appointment came to him entirely unsought.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] This was in 1884, during the administration of President Chester A.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Chandler was presiding over the Navy Department at this time, and it was under his supervision that the four vessels commonly known as the Roach cruisers, the USS *Atlanta*, USS *Boston*, USS *Chicago*, and USS *Dolphin*, were built.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Part of the scheme of building the new navy was the organization of what was known as an advisory board, composed of two civilians and a number of naval officers.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Owing to this regime the bureaus were not given the same free hand that has obtained since the advisory board was discontinued, although they did valuable work in the details of designs.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Forced draft was used on these new vessels, after having been tried on two others—the *Alliance* and *Swatara*—under Loring's direction.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] In 1885, with the advent of a new administration, there was a general spirit of unrest about the Navy Department from what seemed to be a prevailing belief that whatever was, was wrong.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] The air was filled with rumors of intended changes, among them one which promised to cause a violation of the contract labor law, as it was actually seriously under consideration to import a British engineer and put him in charge of the design of machinery.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] From this intent and other indications it became evident to Loring that he did not enjoy the Secretary's confidence, and he tendered his resignation.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] After leaving the Bureau of Steam Engineering he was appointed as a senior member of the Experimental Board of Naval Officers at the New York Navy Yard.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Under his direction, the board conducted competitive tests of water-tube boilers to determine the type that should be used on the coast-defence vessel USS *Monterey*.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Another series of experiments conducted by Loring were those on the boilers of the torpedo boat USS *Cushing*, to determine the economy of evaporation with different air pressures and rates of combustion.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] These experiments have proven of the to be a form of valuable collection of engineering data.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] A number of clever devices had to be schemed out to carry on these tests, and the whole success was credited to Loring and the board.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Having reached the age limit in December 1890, he was placed on the retired list; but having always been a man of very vigorous physique, he did not give up active employment and was for a time consulting engineer to the United States and Brazil Mail Steamship Company.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] During the Spanish–American War he was recalled to active duty and assigned as inspector of engineering work in New York City.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Loring's naval record reflects his active service, though contemporary accounts also emphasize his social activities.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was noted for his public speaking and writing, as well as his participation in social gatherings.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was for two years president of the Engineers' Club of New York, which is a sure test of popularity and wide acquaintance in the engineering world.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was also president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, the highest honor which his branch of the profession could confer.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was a vice-president of the Society of Naval Architects and Marine Engineers from its formation until his death, and, as long as his health permitted, was very active in its council and general meetings.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He was a member of our own Society from the beginning.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] He had also been very active in the Army and Navy Club of New York, filling various offices and acting as its secretary for several years.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Lording succumbed to an attack of paralysis.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] Loring's career covered almost the whole period of progress in marine engineering from the side-wheel engine and box boilers down to the triple-expansion engine and steam turbine, forced draft and the water-tube boiler.
[src:charles-harding-loring/charles-harding-loring] In nearly all of this progress he played an important part, and he had done both his duty and he had been a factor in the continued advancement of the profession and the service he loved.
